ales","Of LlandeiloFawr, Maenordeilo, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llandilofawr, Carmarthenshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of,Ysgeifiog,Flintshire,Wales":"Ysceifiog, Flintshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bryneglwys, Denbighshire, Wales":"Bryneglwys, Denbighshire, Wales","Cilmin Droetu, Wales":"Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","killed":"Killedan, County Mayo, Ierland"},"en":{"ABT    1400–":"about 1400–Deceased","1400–Male":"1400–Deceased","1404–Female":"1404–Deceased","1425–Male":"1425–Deceased","1437–Male":"1437–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1364–Male":"1364–Deceased","1437":"1437","1404":"1404","ABT    1400":"about 1400","1425":"1425","1400":"1400","1364":"1364","ABT    1425":"about 1425","of,Llangernyw,Denbighshire,Wales":"Llangernyw, Denbighshire, Wales","Of LlandeiloFawr, Maenordeilo, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llandilofawr, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of,Ysgeifiog,Flintshire,Wales":"Ysceifiog, Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Bryneglwys, Denbighshire, Wales":"Bryneglwys, Denbighshire, Wales","Cilmin Droetu, Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","killed":"Killedan, County Mayo, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bela","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Hungarian (<b>Béla</b>): from the common Hungarian personal name <i>Béla</i>, which is of uncertain etymology. It may be from the Slavic personal name element <i>bel</i> ‘white’ (see, for example,   Belan  ), or possibly from Turkish <i>bel</i> ‘waist, loins’, also ‘middle of the back’, or <i>belek</i> ‘gift’. The surname <i>Bela</i> is also found in Romania, Slovenia, and Croatia.","Czech (<b>Běla</b>): from the female personal name <i>Běla</i>, meaning ‘white’. As a surname it denoted the son or husband of a woman so named.","Sorbian (<b>Běla</b>, <b>B'ela</b>, or <b>Běła</b>, <b>B'eła</b>): from a pet form of the Biblical personal name   Abel  , or a nickname derived from <i>běły</i> ‘white, bright, fair’. Compare   Biele  ,   Biehle  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Biehle","meanings":["German: possibly a topographic name from <i>Biel</i> ‘sloping rock’, or a habitational name from any of several places called Bielau, in Silesia, or Biehla in eastern Germany, or Biele on the Oder river.","German (Westphalia): topographic name for someone who lived by a field that had the shape of a hatchet, from Middle Low German <i>bīl</i> ‘hatchet, axe’.","Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Běla</b>, <b>B'ela</b>, or <b>Běła</b>, <b>B'eła</b> (see   Bela   3)."]},{"name":"Belan","meanings":["Croatian and Serbian; Slovak (also <b>Belán</b>, <b>Beláň</b>, <b>Belaň</b>) and Czech (<b>Bělán</b>): nickname for someone with white or very fair hair or a pale complexion, derived from (a dialect form of) Croatian <i>bijel</i>, Serbian <i>beo</i>, Slovak <i>biely</i>, and Czech <i>bílý</i> ‘white, light, fair’. The surname may also be derived from the old personal names, such as <i>Belimir</i> (see   Belic  ). In North America, this surname may also be an altered form of the Croatian variant <b>Bjelan</b>. The Sorbian cognate, <b>Bělan</b>, is apparently found in a Germanized form, only (see   Bellan  ).","French (<b>Bélan</b>): altered form of <b>Béland</b> (see   Beland  )."]},{"name":"Belin","meanings":["Czech (<b>Bělín</b>): either a nickname from a dialect derivative of Czech <i>bílý</i> ‘white’ or a derivative of the female personal name <i>Běla</i> (see   Bela  ).","Croatian: cognate of   Belan   and   Belina  . Compare   Bellin  .","French (also <b>Bélin</b>): nickname from a diminutive of <i>bélier</i> ‘ram’, borne by a ram in the medieval literary cycle <i>Reynard the Fox</i> (in French: <i>Roman de Renart</i>)."]}]},{"name":"Gruffudd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffudd","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."]},{"name":"Gruffud","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."]},{"name":"Griffith","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Gruffudd ."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Gruffudd ap Bela was born about 1400, in Ysceifiog, Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom as the son of Makintosh. He had at least 4 sons with Nest ferch Bleddyn. He died in Killedan, County Mayo, Ireland."},"et":{"ABT    1400–":"umbes 1400–Surnud","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1404–Female":"1404–Surnud","1425–Male":"1425–Surnud","1437–Male":"1437–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1364–Male":"1364–Surnud","1437":"1437","1404":"1404","ABT    1400":"umbes 1400","1425":"1425","1400":"1400","1364":"1364","ABT    1425":"umbes 1425","of,Llangernyw,Denbighshire,Wales":"Llangernyw, Denbighshire, Wales","Of LlandeiloFawr, Maenordeilo, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llandilofawr, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of,Ysgeifiog,Flintshire,Wales":"Ysceifiog, Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Bryneglwys, Denbighshire, Wales":"Bryneglwys, Denbighshire, Wales","Cilmin Droetu, Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","killed":"Kil